  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- An intergovernmental organization that sets standards for preventing money laundering\n- Recommends global policies and regulations\n- 39 member jurisdictions\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n- Provide frameworks for international cooperation\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Sets guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provides recommendations for member countries\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish uniform regulations across EU member states\n\nMany countries have also implemented their own national laws, like:\n- United States: Bank Secrecy Act\n- United Kingdom: Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Canada: Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act\n\nThese laws typically require:\n- Customer identification\n- Reporting suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Implementing compliance programs\n\nWhile not a single unified international law, these frameworks create a comprehensive global approach to preventing money laundering.",
